g two lines: there are those who think it is a unique, organic condition caused by Gulf War toxins and those who argue that it is probably a psychological condition that can be seen as part of a larger group of illnesses. Using the methods and perspective of anthropology, with its focus on nuances and subtleties, the author provides a new approach to understanding GWS, one that makes sense of the cultural circumstances, specific and general, which gave rise to the illness.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z9783110998283oZDB-23-BHBO40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785336591?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785336591zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785336591/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BHBOc2000d2013  aZDB-23-GOA